Disney, the brand, has a unique emotional resonance that emanates directly back from their founder. There are no other companies quite like this - maybe Apple is close with Steve, but what is amazing is that Walt died in 1966.
It’s interesting that of the top ten most Instagrammed places, around half are Disney parks.
Before he died, he was working on designing the Experimental Prototype Community of Tomorrow. This was the original EPCOT vision. Had he not died, he would have designed a city.
In just a few years of design, and one year of construction, Walt created a place (Disneyland) that has as many visitors as San Francisco. Think about that.
Walt developed the feature length animation (and popularize sound along with it), harnessed advent of television with entertainment programming, and invented the modern theme park.

Today is Walt Disney’s birthday. He was one of the greatest entrepreneurs of the 20th century. Walt combined art and technology to help people escape their present day and offer a world of imagination and reassurance to millions. The world hasn’t seen the likes of him since.

I want to be clear — we are not infallible. We are a platform built on a foundation of trust. We need to continue innovating on trust to make it harder for the bad actors. The trust of our community is our top priority.

We are expanding manual screening of high-risk reservations flagged by our risk detection models first to North America and then globally next year. This will help stop unauthorized parties before they start.
We are launching a 24/7 neighbor hotline so anyone can call us anytime, anywhere in the world and reach a real person. This hotline will be led by our rapid response team.

We are introducing the Airbnb Guest Guarantee. Starting on 12/15/19, if a guest checks into a listing and it doesn’t meet our accuracy standards, we will rebook them into a listing that is just as nice — and if we can’t, they will get 100% of their money back.

By 12/15/20, every home and every host on Airbnb will have been reviewed, with the objective to verify 100% of listings. Trust on the Internet begins with verifying the accuracy of the information on Internet platforms — this is an important step for our industry.
Airbnb is in the business of trust. We are making the most significant steps in designing trust on our platform since our original design in 2008.
We must do better, and we will. This is unacceptable.

I have directed Margaret Richardson from our Executive Team to oversee this new team and initiate a 10 day sprint to review and accelerate the development and implementation of these new safety initiatives.
Third, we are taking immediate action against users who violate these enhanced guest policies, including removal.
Second, we are creating a dedicated “party house” rapid response team.
